content.text:
Makes sense. `label()` can index into `all_labels()` by matching the variant to a position:

```rust
pub fn label(&self) -> &'static str {
    Record::all_labels()[match self {
        Record::FileHistorySnapshot(_) => 0,
        Record::User(_) => 1,
        // ...
    }]
}
```

But that's fragile — the index must stay in sync with the array order. An alternative: match on the variant and return the same `&'static str` from `all_labels()` by searching:

Actually, the simplest DRY approach is the opposite direction — drop `all_labels()` and derive it. We can't iterate enum variants natively, but we can keep a const array and have `label()` return from it:

```rust
const LABELS: &[&str] = &[
    "file-history-snapshot", "user", "assistant", ...
];

pub fn label(&self) -> &'static str {
    LABELS[match self {
        Record::FileHistorySnapshot(_) => 0,
        Record::User(_) => 1,
        ...
    }]
}

pub fn all_labels() -> &'static [&'static str] {
    LABELS
}
```

One source of truth for the strings. The index approach is a bit brittle but the compiler ensures the match is exhaustive, so adding a variant without updating the match is a compile error. Want me to do this?

